.TH GVEEJAY-RELOADED 1 "July 2026" "Veejay" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
Gveejay Reloaded \- graphical live-performance interface for Veejay
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B gveejay-reloaded
.RI [ OPTIONS ]
.br
.B reloaded
.RI [ OPTIONS ]
.br
.B gveejay
.RI [ OPTIONS ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B Gveejay Reloaded
is the GTK3 graphical interface for Veejay. It is a client for a running
Veejay server and can connect to, control, and disconnect from that server
while Veejay continues to run.
.PP
Reloaded is intended for live video performance, sample-bank operation,
stream control, effect-chain editing, FX animation, MIDI learning, VIMS
messaging, preview management, recording, audio beat detection, external audio
synchronisation, and per-sample audio routing.
.PP
The interface is status-driven. Many controls are refreshed from backend status
messages. When a button, list entry, toggle, slider, or curve returns to a
backend value, the backend state is normally authoritative.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR -a , " --auto-connect"
Auto-connect to locally running Veejay instances.
.TP
.BR -b , " --beta"
Enable beta UI features.
.TP
.BR -g , " --geometry " \fIX,Y\fR
Place the main window at screen position \fIX,Y\fR.
.TP
.BR -h , " --host " \fIHOST\fR
Connect to the given Veejay host. The default host is localhost.
.TP
.BR -L , " --lowband"
Use a low-bandwidth mode. This disables image loading in the sample bank.
.TP
.BR -m , " --midi " \fIFILE\fR
Load a MIDI configuration file.
.TP
.BR -n , " --no-color"
Disable coloured text in console logs.
.TP
.BR -p , " --port " \fIPORT\fR
Connect to the given Veejay port. The default is the compiled default port,
typically 3490.
.TP
.BR -P , " --preview " \fIN\fR
Start with preview enabled. Accepted values are 1 for full size, 2 for half
size, 3 for quarter size, and 4 for one eighth size.
.TP
.BR --sample-pages " " \fIN\fR
Allocate \fIN\fR sample-bank pages. The default is 12 pages. The maximum is
512 pages.
.TP
.BR -s , " --size " \fIN\fR "|" \fICxR\fR "|" \fIC:R\fR "|" \fIC,R\fR
Set sample-bank pages or layout. A single integer sets the number of pages.
A two-number form sets columns and rows. The default layout is 6x2 with 12
pages.
.TP
.BR -v , " --verbose"
Enable more verbose logging.
.TP
.BR -V , " --version"
Print the program version, linked libveejaycore version, and data directory,
then exit.
.TP
.BR -X , " --tracks " \fIN\fR
Set the number of multitrack tracks.
.TP
.BR -t , " --theme " \fIFILE\fR
Load a CSS stylesheet. Use \fBsystem\fR to use the system default theme.
.TP
.BR -S , " --small-as-possible"
Create the smallest possible UI layout.
.TP
.BR -f , " --faster-ui"
Hide unused FX parameter sliders instead of disabling them. This reduces GTK
CPU usage on GTK 3.22.30 and newer builds. This option is available only when
Reloaded was built against a GTK version that supports it.
.SH USER INTERFACE OVERVIEW
The main window is arranged around a live preview, transport controls, a
sample bank, the sequence play grid, effect controls, audio controls, status
indicators, and several notebook panels. The exact panel visibility depends on
the current play mode, selected sample or stream, backend status, compile-time
features, and command-line layout options.
.PP
The top-level menus expose file loading and saving, sample actions, stream
creation, MIDI learning, preferences, video settings, image calibration, VIMS
bundles, help, bug reporting, and application exit.
.PP
The status bar and console logs are part of the UI contract. Refresh, reset,
screenshot, background-mask, beat-detector, audio-sync, sequence-bank, and
VIMS actions should report when the click landed. If the visible UI appears
unchanged after an action, check the status bar and backend log first.
.SH CONNECTION AND PREVIEW
Reloaded can connect to a local or remote Veejay server by host and port. It
can also auto-connect to locally running instances when requested.
.PP
Preview can be enabled at startup with \fB--preview\fR or toggled from the UI.
Preview quality uses the levels full, half, quarter, and one eighth. The
preview panel also exposes greyscale and alpha-only preview modes, preview
speed, preview scale, and preview dimensions where available.
.PP
In multitrack mode, preview toggling is routed through the multitrack preview
manager so the visible preview reflects the selected track and master track.
.SH TRANSPORT AND TIMELINE
The transport controls provide forward playback, backward playback, stop,
previous and next frame, previous and next second, and jump-to-start or
jump-to-end actions.
.PP
The timeline and marker area use local frame indices. Selection in/out markers
are inclusive: a marker from 0 to 20 covers frames 0 through 20.
.TP
.B Left mouse button on the playhead triangle
Move or drag the playhead.
.TP
.B Left mouse button on the track
Set or drag the IN point.
.TP
.B Right mouse button on the track
Set or drag the OUT point.
.TP
.B Middle mouse button inside a selection
Enter bound scratch mode. The selection moves as a rigid block; wheel input
resizes the marker while the scratch box is active. Middle-click again to
leave the mode.
.TP
.B Double left click
Clear the current local selection.
.TP
.B Mouse wheel
Move the playhead by the default frame step. Wheel input is ignored while a
mouse button is physically held.
.TP
.B Ctrl + mouse wheel
Move the playhead by about one second.
.TP
.B Shift + mouse wheel
Move the playhead by about two seconds.
.PP
The speed slider controls playback speed. The slow-motion slider divides the
current frame rate by the selected multiplier. Ctrl-clicking these sliders
resets them to neutral.
.SH SAMPLE BANK
The sample bank provides quick access to sample and stream slots. Slots can be
selected, played, and populated from selected sources.
.TP
.B Left or right click
Play a slot.
.TP
.B Shift + left click
Place the currently selected sample or stream into a slot.
.TP
.B Double click
Play the sample or stream in the slot.
.TP
.B Shift + left click on a populated slot
Set the slot as the current mixing channel.
.PP
The active bank selector changes the visible sample-bank page. The default
layout is 6 columns by 2 rows. The default number of pages is 12. In
low-bandwidth mode, sample images are not loaded.
.SH SAMPLE AND STREAM PANELS
The sample panel shows sample title, start and end positions, playback speed,
slow-motion multiplier, hold-frame controls, sample audio volume, transitions,
transition shape, transition length, loop stop, stream buffering links, and
offline recording length.
.PP
The stream panel shows stream timecode, duration, codec information, recording
options, transition settings, camera controls, video-device controls, solid
stream controls, generator parameters, and stream recording progress when the
selected source supports those controls.
.PP
Live capture controls include brightness, contrast, hue, saturation, gamma,
gain, RGB balance, automatic white balance, sharpness, backlight compensation,
automatic gain, automatic hue, temperature, flips, exposure, black level, and
whiteness. Unsupported camera controls may be hidden or insensitive.
.SH SEQUENCE PLAY GRID
The sequence play grid contains four sequence banks, each with one hundred
slots. It is designed for arranging and repeating a bank chain during live
performance or recording.
.PP
The toolbar contains \fBPlay Grid\fR, sequence recording controls, bank toggles,
\fBClear Bank\fR, \fBClear All\fR, \fBCopy Bank\fR, \fBPaste Bank\fR, and
\fBRefresh\fR. Checking a bank includes it in chained playback and also makes
it the active bank. The active bank stays checked.
.TP
.B Left click on a bank header
Select and activate that bank.
.TP
.B Right click on a bank header
Open the bank actions menu.
.TP
.B Left click on an empty cell
Assign the current sample or stream to that sequence slot.
.TP
.B Shift + left click on a cell
Clear the filled cell.
.TP
.B Left drag
Select a range of cells in the current bank.
.TP
.B Ctrl + left drag
Add or remove cells from the current selection.
.TP
.B Alt + drag a filled cell
Swap it with another slot in the same bank.
.TP
.B Right click
Open an actions menu for assign, delete, copy, cut, paste, copy-to-bank,
copy-bank, paste-bank, clear-bank, and refresh operations.
.TP
.B Cursor keys
Move the selected cell.
.TP
.B Ctrl + cursor keys
Extend the current cell selection in the arrow direction.
.TP
.B Alt + 1 .. Alt + 4
Select and target sequence bank 1 through 4.
.TP
.B Delete or Backspace
Clear the selected filled slot or selected filled range.
.TP
.B Enter
Assign the current sample or stream to the selected empty slot.
.TP
.B Ctrl + C, Ctrl + X, Ctrl + V
Copy, cut, or paste selected slot cells.
.TP
.B Ctrl + Shift + C, Ctrl + Shift + V
Copy or paste a whole sequence bank.
.PP
Tooltips on cells identify the assigned sample or stream, title, source type,
length where available, bank number, and slot number.
.SH EFFECTS AND FX CHAIN
The FX panel lists available effects and exposes the current chain. Effects
are grouped into mixing effects, image effects, alpha effects, video effects,
and related categories.
.TP
.B Double click an effect
Add the effect to the current chain entry.
.TP
.B Shift + double click
Add the effect disabled.
.TP
.B Ctrl + double click
Add the effect to the selected sample.
.TP
.B Effect filter entry
Filter the effects list by text.
.PP
Each selected effect exposes up to sixteen parameters, named p0 through p15
unless the effect supplies more specific names. Parameter sliders, increment
and decrement controls, RGB key controls, opacity controls, and mixing-source
controls are updated from the selected chain entry.
.PP
The FX chain panel can enable or disable effect-chain processing for the
current sample or stream. Global chain controls, chain copy, and chain level
controls apply to shared chain operations.
.PP
Beat-aware FX entries have a beat-control toggle. Enabling beat control marks
the selected chain entry as eligible for beat-guided Auto FX modulation. The
beat detector can also enable this toggle automatically when a compatible beat
action is selected.
.SH FX ANIMATION CURVE
The FX animation panel edits parameter animation curves for the selected FX
chain entry and selected parameter. It provides start and end positions,
linear, spline, and freehand modes, per-parameter enable/disable,
chain-entry enable/disable, predefined shape generation, and live preview
traces.
.PP
The selected FX parameter combo chooses the animated parameter. A special chain
opacity target may be edited without requiring a normal FX id. For normal FX
parameters, a valid selected chain entry and effect are required.
.PP
Start and end positions are frame numbers. If the end position is lower than
the start position, Reloaded stores the animation over the same inclusive range
with the endpoints swapped. If both positions are equal, nothing is stored.
.PP
The curve editor has two visible states. With no parameter selected, it shows
the live beat or FX overview. With a parameter selected, it edits that
parameter and shows the stored or previewed curve for the current entry.
.PP
Predefined shapes immediately switch the editor into freehand curve data and
mark the curve locally dirty. Shape generation uses the current sample or
stream range, the selected parameter's legal min/max range, bound-min and
bound-max, the Steps value, Seed, Detail, and Reverse. The generated preview is
local until it is stored.
.PP
Predefined shapes include No shape, Bounce, Burst Envelope, Cosine, Sine,
Damped Sine, Ease In, Ease Out, Exponential, Gaussian, Noise, Pulse, Ramp Drop,
Random Burst, Random Inertia, Random Mean, Random Quantized, Random Smooth,
Random Walk, Sawtooth, Shape Steps, Smooth, Smooth Noise, Square, and ZigZag.
.PP
The Steps control changes the number of shape repetitions or quantisation
steps, depending on the selected shape. The Seed control affects random and
noise-based shapes. The Detail control affects generated shape detail. The
Shuffle button tries new seeds and avoids visually identical random motifs
when possible.
.TP
.B Store
Serialises the visible curve over the inclusive frame range, clamps every
point to the selected parameter's legal min/max, sends the keyframe packet to
the backend, enables the parameter animation, and leaves the stored curve in
live-preview override mode.
.TP
.B Enable parameter
Enable or disable animation for the selected parameter on the selected entry.
This does not create a new curve by itself.
.TP
.B Enable entry
Enable or disable FX animation for the selected chain entry. The same state is
mirrored between the FX chain and FX animation controls.
.TP
.B Clear parameter
Clear only the selected parameter animation for the current keyframe entry.
.TP
.B Clear entry
Reset all keyframes for the selected FX entry.
.PP
The curve widget shows frame, value, and timecode near the active marker. Live
traces can be shown as underlays or as the current live overview. User edits
and stored curves can override the live trace until a later backend refresh or
clear operation restores backend-authoritative display.
.SH AUDIO OUTPUT
Reloaded's audio controls are split into global default output, per-sample
overrides, JACK master level, and recording source. These are separate
concepts and should not be treated as one volume or route.
.PP
The global audio source selector chooses the default source used when the
current sample does not have its own saved audio route:
.TP
.B Original video audio
Use the audio track associated with the current sample or stream.
.TP
.B JACK external
Use JACK as the external audio provider. The JACK master volume control sends
the external master volume only while this source is selected.
.TP
.B WAV file
Use a configured WAV file as the external audio provider. WAV paths are stored
through the WAV profile controls described below.
.TP
.B Silence
Use no audible source. Silence cannot be analysed by the beat detector.
.PP
Selecting Original disables external playback and returns the sync mode to off.
Selecting JACK or WAV makes the external-provider controls relevant. Selecting
WAV also exposes the WAV path, loop, and profile controls.
.PP
The status area reports whether the active route is global, internal beat
analysis, an external JACK/WAV route, or a sample-specific route.
.SH AUDIO MIXING
The audio mixer chooses how Original audio and the external provider are heard
when the global default route is active. It is independent from per-sample
audio-route storage.
.TP
.B Follow
Follow the backend/default route. The manual route radio buttons are disabled
and the crossfade is inactive.
.TP
.B Original
Force Original audio for the audible route. The crossfade is set to 0.
.TP
.B External / JACK
Force the external provider for the audible route. The crossfade is set to
100. The label may refer to JACK even when the external-provider source is a
WAV profile, because both are handled as the external master route.
.TP
.B Original + External
Mix Original and the external provider. If the crossfade is still at an
endpoint, Reloaded moves it to 50 when this mode is selected.
.TP
.B Crossfade
Controls the Original/External blend only in Original + External mode. It is
inactive in Follow, Original, and External-only modes.
.PP
Mixer mode and crossfade are restored from backend status. Manual changes send
separate VIMS updates for mixer mode and, when needed, crossfade.
.SH WAV PROFILES AND PER-SAMPLE AUDIO ROUTES
Reloaded has four WAV profile slots. A profile stores a WAV path and whether
that WAV should loop. The path must be safe for VIMS transport; paths with the
VIMS command separator or control newlines are rejected.
.TP
.B WAV profile slot 1 .. 4
Store or clear a WAV path and loop flag. These slots are reusable global
profiles; they are also the selectable WAV sources for per-sample routes.
.TP
.B Sample source: Follow global/default
Clear the sample's own audio route. The sample then uses the global default
source.
.TP
.B Sample source: Original
Save an explicit original-audio override for the sample.
.TP
.B Sample source: WAV
Bind the sample to one of WAV profile slots 1 through 4. Slot 0 means no WAV
profile and cannot arm a WAV sample route.
.TP
.B Sample source: JACK
Bind the sample to JACK external audio.
.TP
.B Sample source: Silence
Bind the sample to silence from a stored frame anchor.
.PP
Per-sample external routes use the same external mode names as global Audio
Sync: Queue/Monitor, Analyze External Tempo, Clean Monitor, Monitor +
Trickplay, Visual Tempo Follow, Tempo Match Bridge, and Track Align.
.PP
.B Set Here
stores the selected sample route at the current video frame. For WAV routes it
also stores the current WAV anchor in milliseconds. The status label reports
routes such as Sample Original, WAV slot N with mode and switch frame, JACK
with mode and switch frame, or Silence with switch frame.
.PP
.B Rearm
re-sends the saved route for the selected sample. For WAV routes, the selected
profile must be greater than 0. Clearing a sample route returns it to
Follow global/default.
.SH AUDIO BEAT DETECTOR
The Audio Beat Detector analyses the selected audio source and can drive visual
and transport actions. It analyses Original video audio when that source is
selected, or the selected JACK/WAV external provider when JACK or WAV is used.
Silence cannot be analysed.
.TP
.B Enable beat detector
Start or stop beat analysis. Enabling it may adjust sync controls to keep the
chosen source/action combination valid.
.TP
.B Action: none
Analyse without beat-driven transport or Auto FX action.
.TP
.B Action: auto FX
Drive beat-aware FX modulation only. This is the safe beat action for Original
video audio.
.TP
.B Action: break beat (Auto FX)
Use Break Beat transport/scratch behaviour and keep Auto FX modulation active.
This action requires JACK external or WAV input.
.TP
.B Action: break beat
Use Break Beat transport/scratch behaviour without Auto FX modulation. This
action requires JACK external or WAV input.
.TP
.B Input channels
Set the number of external input channels analysed when JACK is the selected
provider.
.TP
.B Threshold
Set the transient strength required to accept a beat or break-beat hit. The
label changes with the selected action.
.TP
.B Cooldown
Set the minimum time between accepted beat hits or break-beat turns.
.TP
.B Hold Window
Set the open/hold window used by Break Beat. It is inactive for Auto FX only.
.TP
.B Pulse
Set the short pulse envelope used by beat-aware FX and Break Beat scratch
emphasis.
.TP
.B Gate
Set the held gate or repeat-memory window used by beat-aware FX and Break Beat.
.TP
.B Auto FX mode
Choose off, primary, primary + motion, motion + memory, or chaos. Higher modes
select more motion, memory, and chaos-oriented beat-hint roles.
.TP
.B Auto FX amount
Set the global intensity of automatic beat-driven parameter modulation.
.TP
.B Scratch sensitivity
Set Break Beat scratch sensitivity.
.TP
.B Source-loss pause
Pause Break Beat response when the selected source is lost.
.TP
.B Monitor latency / Auto latency
Automatically estimate monitor latency for the JACK monitor path, or disable
auto latency and calibrate it manually. Manual latency is available only for
Break Beat actions.
.TP
.B Refresh
Request a fresh Audio Beat status print from the backend. This refreshes
analysis state reporting but does not rebuild Auto FX mapping.
.TP
.B Reset Auto FX
Forget the current automatic FX mapping. The next beat or update rebuilds the
Auto FX target set from the current effect chain.
.PP
Live beat values show level, envelope, transient, flux, bass, mid, high, gate,
pulse, estimated BPM, accepted hit count, age since last accepted hit, sample
rate, monotonic hit sequence, and monitor latency.
.SH AUTO FX
Auto FX maps the current chain using beat hints. Beat hints are role metadata
supplied by effects. The automatic mode determines how aggressively parameter
roles are selected. The automatic amount controls the global intensity of
beat-driven modulation.
.PP
Auto FX does not replace manual FX editing. It modulates eligible parameters on
beat-controlled entries while the underlying effect parameters remain visible
and manually adjustable.
.SH AUDIO SYNC
The Audio Sync panel controls external audio analysis, monitoring,
synchronisation, and per-sample route state. The external provider can be JACK
input or one of the configured WAV profile slots.
.PP
Audio sync modes include:
.TP
.B Off
Disable external audio synchronisation and return to the last non-external
master source where applicable.
.TP
.B Analyze External Tempo
Listen to the external provider only. This exports BPM, phase, and control
information without forcing external audio playback.
.TP
.B Clean Monitor
Play external audio unchanged as a monitor source.
.TP
.B Monitor + Trickplay
Make external audio follow transport behaviour such as pause, reverse, speed,
SFD, and rate changes.
.TP
.B Visual Tempo Follow
Drive video timing and beat-aware FX from the external tempo without stretching
the external audio.
.TP
.B Tempo Match Bridge
Stretch the external audio to match the target tempo and phase. Controls
include target BPM, phase, confidence, and maximum correction.
.TP
.B Track Align
Use waveform correlation to align the selected clip or video against the
external master track.
.PP
The source selector chooses JACK or WAV as the external provider source. WAV
mode uses the configured path, selected profile slot, and optional looping. The
status area shows enabled, open, running, mode, source, channel count, sample
rate, audible route, BPM, confidence, bridge activity, ratio, correction,
target BPM, target confidence, maximum correction, bridge state, track lock,
track offset, track confidence, track correction, track state, phase, level,
and transient information.
.PP
When a sample has its own audio route, the panel title and route labels change
to show that the sample route overrides the global default for that sample.
.SH RECORDING
Recording controls choose the audio source for disk recording, including
automatic, original audio, external JACK/WAV provider, or silence where
available. Sample and stream recording controls have separate source selectors.
.PP
Sequence recording records the current sequence-bank playback into a new
sample. The sequence toolbar exposes start, stop, and progress controls for
this route.
.SH MEDIA AND STREAM CREATION
The Media panel lists Veejay's working directory. Double-clicking a row adds it
as a sample.
.PP
The stream menu and input-stream dialog can create or open live input streams,
YUV4MPEG streams, FFmpeg/AVFormat streams, solid streams, generators, and
remote Veejay-to-Veejay network sources. The generator dialog exposes the
available generator list and generator parameters.
.SH VIDEO SETTINGS
The Video Settings dialog contains screenshot dimensions, preview scaling,
primary SDL video-window options, fullscreen settings, aspect-ratio controls,
window offsets, and video loopback settings.
.SH IMAGE CALIBRATION
The Image Calibration dialog captures dark, light, and flat frames for live
stream calibration. It can run calibration globally or per stream and provides
reset, capture, and save controls. Calibration requires a selected live stream.
.SH VIMS MESSENGER, BUNDLES, AND MACROS
The VIMS messenger sends VIMS commands directly to the backend. Bundle editing
allows stored VIMS command groups to be edited and reused. The VIMS scheduler
can fire messages at selected frame, duplicate-frame, or loop positions.
.PP
Macro controls can record, play, stop, clear, delay, and loop VIMS-driven UI
actions. Macro start and stop actions report their state through the status
bar and console logs.
.SH MIDI
The MIDI menu enables MIDI learning, toggles MIDI support, clears the MIDI
layout, saves the MIDI layout, and loads an existing MIDI layout. Many UI
controls register their corresponding VIMS command when MIDI learning is
active.
.PP
MIDI-learned toggles use release-aware behaviour where supported, so note-off
or zero-value controller events do not accidentally retrigger one-shot toggle
actions.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I gveejay.reloaded.glade
GTK3 Glade UI definition loaded at startup.
.TP
.I gveejay.reloaded.css
Default Reloaded stylesheet.
.TP
.I MIDI layout files
User-saved MIDI mappings loaded or saved from the MIDI menu or command line.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Start Reloaded and auto-connect to a local Veejay server:
.B gveejay-reloaded --auto-connect
.TP
Connect to a remote server on a custom port:
.B gveejay-reloaded --host 192.168.1.20 --port 3490
.TP
Start with quarter-size preview and a small UI:
.B gveejay-reloaded --preview 3 --small-as-possible
.TP
Use the system GTK theme instead of Reloaded's CSS:
.B gveejay-reloaded --theme system
.TP
Use a custom CSS file and load a MIDI layout:
.B gveejay-reloaded --theme ./dark-live.css --midi ./layout.xml
.TP
Start with the default 6x2 grid and 24 sample-bank pages:
.B gveejay-reloaded --size 24
.TP
Start with a two-column by four-row sample-bank layout:
.B gveejay-reloaded --size 2x4
.TP
Use colon or comma layout syntax:
.B gveejay-reloaded --size 3:4
.br
.B gveejay-reloaded --size 3,4
.SH BUGS
Report bugs through the Veejay issue tracker. When reporting UI bugs, include
the Reloaded version, GTK version, backend version, the selected play mode,
whether the selected item is a sample or stream, the active audio source, the
selected audio-sync or beat action if relevant, whether a sample-specific audio
route is active, and any status-bar or console messages printed after the
action.
